  'china-festivals-april-may-2026': {
    title: 'China Festivals April & May 2026: Celebrations, Culture & Top Visiting Countries',
    category: 'Travel Tips', date: 'Apr 14, 2026', emoji: '🇨🇳',
    readTime: '7 min read',
    desc: 'Discover the biggest spring festivals in China and how to stay connected during your visit.',
    sections: [
      { h: 'Spring Festivals in China: April & May 2026', body: `Spring is one of the most vibrant times to visit China. April and May bring a string of national holidays, cultural festivals, and local celebrations that offer a unique window into Chinese culture. Here\'s what to expect and how to make the most of your visit.` },
      { h: 'Qingming Festival (Tomb Sweeping Day) — Early April', body: `Qingming (清明节) falls on April 4–5, 2026. It\'s a public holiday when Chinese families visit the graves of ancestors to clean, pay respects, and make offerings. While solemnly observed in cemeteries, the festival also coincides with spring outings and kite flying as families enjoy the season. Parks across China are packed with families picnicking and enjoying cherry blossoms. Beijing\'s parks and West Lake in Hangzhou are particularly stunning during this period.` },
      { h: 'Labour Day Golden Week — May 1–5', body: `China\'s Labour Day holiday (劳动节) has been extended to a 5-day "mini Golden Week" running May 1–5, 2026. This is one of the busiest travel periods in China, with hundreds of millions of domestic tourists taking trips. Popular destinations like the Great Wall, the Terracotta Warriors in Xi\'an, and Zhangjiajie National Park see huge crowds.\n\nIf you\'re visiting China during this period, book accommodation and transport well in advance. Popular tourist spots will be packed but also beautifully festive.` },
      { h: 'Connectivity in China — What You Need to Know', body: `Staying connected in China presents unique challenges. The "Great Firewall" blocks popular Western services including Google, WhatsApp, Facebook, Instagram, and many VPN services. Here\'s how to navigate this:\n\n**WoWo SIM China eSIM:** Our China-specific data plans give you reliable internet access. However, accessing blocked apps still requires a VPN that works in China — set this up before arriving as the App Store/Google Play may be restricted once you\'re in-country.\n\n**WeChat is essential:** Download WeChat before you travel. It\'s the primary messaging, payments, and social media platform in China. Chinese restaurants, shops, and transport often require WeChat Pay.\n\n**Offline is your friend:** Download offline maps (Baidu Maps works in China), translation apps with offline mode, and your itinerary before arrival.` },
      { h: 'Top Destinations for Spring 2026', body: `**Beijing:** Visit the Great Wall (avoid May holiday crowds — go early morning), the Forbidden City, and the Temple of Heaven. Cherry blossoms line the streets in April.\n\n**Chengdu:** See pandas at the Giant Panda Research Base, explore Jinli Ancient Street, and eat authentic Sichuan hotpot.\n\n**Guilin and Yangshuo:** The famous karst limestone landscape along the Li River is at its most lush and green in spring. Take a cruise or cycle through the countryside.\n\n**Shanghai:** The city\'s museums, French Concession, and Bund waterfront are vibrant year-round. Spring means comfortable temperatures and fewer tourists than summer.` },
    ],
