  'japan-visa-americans-2026': {
    title: 'Japan Visa for Americans: Do You Need One? 2026 Entry Guide',
    category: 'Travel Tips', date: 'Apr 13, 2026', emoji: '🇯🇵',
    readTime: '6 min read',
    desc: 'Complete guide to Japan entry requirements for US citizens in 2026 including visa-free travel rules.',
    sections: [
      { h: 'Do Americans Need a Visa for Japan?', body: `Great news for US travelers: American citizens do NOT need a visa to visit Japan for tourism or business purposes. Under the Japan-US visa exemption agreement, US passport holders can enter Japan visa-free for stays of up to 90 days.\n\nThis visa waiver has been in place for decades and remains valid as of 2026. Simply show your valid US passport at immigration, state that your visit is for tourism, and you\'ll receive a stamp allowing a 90-day stay.` },
      { h: 'Entry Requirements for Americans in 2026', body: `To enter Japan visa-free, American travelers need:\n\n**Valid US Passport:** Your passport must be valid for the duration of your stay in Japan. Japan does not require 6 months validity — it just needs to cover your planned travel dates.\n\n**Return/Onward Ticket:** Immigration officers may ask to see proof of a return flight or onward travel. Have your booking confirmation accessible.\n\n**Proof of Funds:** While rarely checked, you should theoretically be able to demonstrate you have sufficient funds for your stay (roughly $100 USD per day is a commonly cited guideline).\n\n**No Criminal Record:** Travelers with certain criminal convictions may be denied entry. Japan is strict about this.` },
      { h: 'Japan\'s Visit Japan Web — Register Before You Fly', body: `Japan\'s digital immigration system "Visit Japan Web" allows travelers to pre-register their passport details, customs declaration, and quarantine information before arrival. This significantly speeds up the immigration and customs process.\n\nRegister at vjw-lp.digital.go.jp before your trip. It takes about 20 minutes and the QR codes you receive let you breeze through arrival formalities faster.` },
      { h: 'Staying Connected in Japan', body: `Japan has excellent 4G LTE and 5G coverage in cities, though rural areas can have patchy connectivity. The best options for staying connected:\n\n**WoWo SIM Japan eSIM:** Our Japan eSIM plans connect to top local networks including NTT Docomo and SoftBank. Plans start from $4.50 for 1GB and go up to unlimited data for longer stays. The eSIM is installed before you leave home and activates the moment you land at Narita, Haneda, or Kansai airports.\n\n**Pocket WiFi:** A portable WiFi router is an alternative but requires returning the device at the end of your trip and usually costs more than an eSIM.\n\n**Local SIM card:** Available at airports but requires waiting in queues. eSIM is far more convenient.` },
      { h: 'Practical Tips for Visiting Japan', body: `**Cash is still king:** While digital payments are growing, many traditional restaurants, temples, and small shops in Japan are still cash-only. Withdraw yen at 7-Eleven ATMs, which reliably accept foreign cards.\n\n**IC Cards:** Get a Suica or Pasmo card (rechargeable transit cards) at any airport for seamless travel on trains, subways, and even convenience store purchases in major cities.\n\n**Etiquette matters:** Remove shoes when entering homes and traditional restaurants, bow as a greeting, avoid eating while walking, and keep voices low on public transport.\n\n**Language:** Download Google Translate with Japanese offline. The camera translation feature is invaluable for reading menus and signs.` },
