    desc: 'Everything European travelers need to know about visiting Morocco in 2026.',
    sections: [
      { h: 'Do Europeans Need a Visa for Morocco?', body: `Citizens of most EU and European countries do NOT need a visa to visit Morocco for stays of up to 90 days. This visa exemption applies to passport holders from France, Germany, Spain, Italy, Netherlands, Belgium, Portugal, UK, Ireland, and most other European nations.\n\nNon-EU European countries including Switzerland, Norway, and Iceland also typically enjoy visa-free access to Morocco. Always verify with the Moroccan embassy for your specific nationality before travel.` },
      { h: 'What to Expect at Moroccan Immigration', body: `Entering Morocco is generally straightforward for Europeans. At the border (whether by air at Casablanca Mohammed V, Marrakech, or Agadir airports, or by ferry from Spain):\n\n• Present your valid European passport\n• Fill in the arrival card (provided on the plane/ferry)\n• State the purpose of your visit (tourism)\n• You may be asked about accommodation — have your hotel name ready\n\nYou\'ll receive a stamp permitting a 90-day stay in Morocco.` },
      { h: 'Connectivity in Morocco', body: `Morocco has solid 4G LTE coverage in cities and tourist areas. Marrakech, Casablanca, Fes, and Agadir have excellent connectivity. Remote desert areas and the Atlas Mountains have limited or no coverage.\n\n**WoWo SIM Morocco eSIM:** Our Morocco plans provide reliable data through top local networks. Plans start from $5.00 with options for data-only connections during your entire trip. Buy before you leave — no queue at the airport, QR code in your email within seconds.\n\nAlternatively, local SIM cards from Maroc Telecom, Orange Maroc, or Inwi are available at airports and in cities, typically providing good value for longer stays.` },
      { h: 'Essential Tips for Visiting Morocco', body: `**Respect local customs:** Morocco is a predominantly Muslim country. Dress modestly when visiting medinas, mosques, and rural areas. Shoulders and knees should be covered. During Ramadan (dates vary annually), be respectful of those fasting.\n\n**Bargaining is normal:** In souks (markets), prices are rarely fixed. Polite negotiation is expected and part of the experience. Start at around 50–60% of the asking price.\n\n**Learn basic French/Arabic phrases:** French is widely spoken in Morocco's cities, especially for business and tourism. A few words of Arabic (marhaba = hello, shukran = thank you) go a long way.\n\n**Dirham currency:** The Moroccan dirham (MAD) is not exchangeable outside Morocco. Change money on arrival at banks or exchange offices (avoid touts offering informal exchange).` },
