      { h: 'Visa Options for Australians Visiting Indonesia', body: `**Free Visa on Arrival (30 days):** Available at Ngurah Rai (Bali), Soekarno-Hatta (Jakarta), Juanda (Surabaya), and other major entry points. Present your Australian passport, return ticket, and proof of accommodation.\n\n**E-VOA (Online VOA):** Apply in advance at molina.imigrasi.go.id. Costs the same as on-arrival ($35 USD) but saves time queuing at the airport. Recommended for peak travel season.\n\n**Visit Visa (60+ days):** For longer stays, apply for a B211A Tourist/Visitor Visa through an Indonesian embassy or visa agent before departure. Allows up to 60 days with extension possibilities.` },
      { h: 'Staying Connected in Indonesia', body: `Indonesia is a vast archipelago with varying connectivity quality. Bali, Jakarta, and major tourist areas have excellent 4G LTE. Rural areas and smaller islands may have limited coverage.\n\n**WoWo SIM Indonesia eSIM:** The easiest way to get connected. Plans start from $4.00 and provide access through Indonesia\'s top networks. Buy before you depart, scan the QR code, and you\'re connected the moment you land. No queuing, no fumbling with physical SIMs on arrival.\n\n**Local SIM options:** Telkomsel, XL Axiata, and Indosat Ooredoo offer tourist SIM packages at airports. These are good value but require standing in queues on arrival.` },
      { h: 'What to Know Before Visiting Bali', body: `**Currency:** Indonesian Rupiah (IDR). ATMs are widely available in Bali and Jakarta. Be cautious of "dynamic currency conversion" scams at ATMs — always choose to be charged in IDR.\n\n**Scams to avoid:** Unofficial taxi drivers at Bali airport charge inflated rates. Use the official taxi counter inside the arrivals hall or use Grab/Gojek (Indonesia\'s ride-sharing apps).\n\n**Motorbike rentals:** Popular for exploring Bali independently. Ensure you have an international driving permit or the relevant motorbike license. Wear a helmet.\n\n**Offender Temple etiquette:** When visiting temples (puras), wear a sarong (often provided at temple entrances). Women are generally asked not to enter during menstruation.` },
