  'china-visa-europeans-2026': {
    title: 'China Visa Requirements for European Citizens: Complete 2026 Entry Guide',
    category: 'Informative', date: 'Apr 6, 2026', emoji: '🇨🇳',
    readTime: '7 min read',
    desc: 'Detailed visa requirements, application process, and connectivity guide for European citizens visiting China in 2026.',
    sections: [
      { h: 'Do Europeans Need a Visa for China?', body: `The situation changed significantly in 2024–2026. China has implemented a visa-free policy for short-term stays for citizens of many European countries. As of 2026, the following EU/European countries enjoy visa-free entry to China for stays of up to 15 days (recently extended to 30 days in some cases): France, Germany, Italy, Spain, Netherlands, Belgium, Portugal, Austria, Switzerland, Ireland, and more.\n\nAlways verify the current policy at the Chinese embassy in your country before traveling, as visa policies can change.` },
      { h: 'Standard Tourist Visa (L Visa) for China', body: `For countries not covered by the visa-free arrangement, or for stays longer than the visa-free period, you\'ll need a Chinese tourist visa (L Visa).\n\n**Application process:**\n1. Complete the online application form at the Visa Application Service Center website\n2. Book an appointment at a Chinese Visa Application Service Center (CVASC) or Chinese Embassy/Consulate\n3. Attend your appointment with required documents\n4. Collect your visa (typically 4–7 working days)\n\n**Required documents:** Valid passport (6+ months validity), completed application form, recent passport photos, flight itinerary, hotel bookings, bank statements, travel insurance.\n\n**Visa fees:** Approximately €80–€120 depending on nationality and visa type.` },
      { h: 'Connectivity Challenge: China\'s Great Firewall', body: `Internet access in China is heavily restricted by the "Great Firewall." The following services are blocked: Google (Search, Maps, Gmail, YouTube), Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp, Twitter/X, and many Western news sites.\n\n**What works without a VPN:** WeChat, Weibo, Baidu, local Chinese apps, most banking apps, and basic browsing of Chinese websites.\n\n**VPN:** Technically required to access blocked services. Set up a working VPN (ExpressVPN and NordVPN have China-specific servers) BEFORE arriving in China, as downloading VPNs from within China is difficult.\n\n**WoWo SIM China eSIM:** Provides reliable data connectivity through local Chinese networks. However, VPN access to blocked services is a separate matter governed by Chinese regulations.` },
      { h: 'Practical Essentials for China Travel', body: `**WeChat is mandatory:** Set up WeChat (including WeChat Pay) before arrival. Nearly every merchant, restaurant, and attraction in China accepts WeChat Pay. Link your international credit card to WeChat Pay for convenience.\n\n**Alipay:** The other major digital payment platform. Also useful to set up before arrival.\n\n**Translation:** Download Google Translate with offline Chinese language pack. Pleco is an excellent dedicated Chinese dictionary app.\n\n**Emergency contacts:** Save the number of your country\'s embassy in China. The police emergency number is 110, medical emergency is 120.` },
    ],
