  'how-to-make-travel-itinerary': {
    title: 'How to Make a Travel Itinerary: A Step-by-Step Guide for Smarter Trips',
    category: 'Travel Tips', date: 'Mar 27, 2026', emoji: '📋',
    readTime: '8 min read',
    desc: 'Step-by-step guide to planning the perfect travel itinerary for any destination.',
    sections: [
      { h: 'Why a Good Itinerary Matters', body: `A well-crafted travel itinerary is the difference between a stressful trip and a seamless adventure. It doesn\'t have to mean scheduling every hour — in fact, the best itineraries build in flexibility. The goal is to have a framework that ensures you see what you came for, with breathing room for spontaneous discoveries along the way.` },
      { h: 'Step 1: Define Your Trip Goals', body: `Before opening a single booking website, ask yourself:\n\n• **What type of traveler am I?** Do you prefer cultural immersion, adventure activities, relaxation, food experiences, or a mix?\n• **How many days do I have?** Be realistic about travel time between destinations.\n• **What\'s my budget?** This determines accommodation quality, dining choices, and activities.\n• **Who am I traveling with?** Solo, couple, family, or group trips require very different planning approaches.\n\nWrite down your top 5 "must see/do" experiences for the destination. These become the anchor points of your itinerary.` },
      { h: 'Step 2: Research Your Destination', body: `Use a mix of resources for thorough research:\n\n**Guidebooks:** Lonely Planet and Rough Guides offer structured, reliable destination information.\n**Travel blogs:** First-hand experiences from recent travelers are invaluable. Search "[destination] travel guide [current year]" for up-to-date advice.\n**YouTube:** Video guides give a visual sense of destinations and activities.\n**Reddit:** The r/travel and destination-specific subreddits contain candid traveler experiences and advice.\n**Google Maps:** Use the "Saved" feature to bookmark restaurants, hotels, and attractions. This becomes a visual map of your itinerary.` },
      { h: 'Step 3: Plan Logistics First', body: `Book your anchor points before filling in the details:\n\n1. **Flights:** Book in advance for the best prices. Use Google Flights to track prices and set alerts.\n2. **Accommodation:** Prioritize location. Staying central costs more but saves time and transport costs. Book refundable rates where possible.\n3. **Internal transport:** Research train passes, domestic flights, or car rental. Book popular routes (like the Shinkansen in Japan or Eurostar) well in advance.\n4. **Key attractions:** For popular sites with timed entry (Colosseum, Sagrada Família, Uffizi Gallery), book tickets months ahead.` },
      { h: 'Step 4: Build Your Day-by-Day Plan', body: `With logistics confirmed, build your itinerary:\n\n• **Group activities by location:** Avoid zigzagging across a city. Cluster morning activities near each other, afternoon activities in another area.\n• **Build in buffer time:** Flights run late, queues form, restaurants close. Build 30–60 minute buffers between activities.\n• **Plan slower days:** Not every day needs to be packed. A slow morning at a local café or an afternoon reading in a park refreshes you for the next day.\n• **Keep digital and physical copies:** Save your itinerary to Google Drive, your phone\'s notes app, and print a copy for emergencies.` },
      { h: 'Step 5: Connectivity — Staying Online During Your Trip', body: `Modern travel relies heavily on having reliable internet: navigation, translations, booking changes, communicating with home. Plan your connectivity before you leave:\n\n**WoWo SIM eSIM:** The simplest solution for international travelers. Buy a data plan for your destination before departure, receive a QR code, scan it in your phone settings, and you\'re connected the moment you land. Plans start from $3.50 and cover 195+ countries.\n\n**Download offline essentials:** Before traveling, download offline maps (Google Maps), translation packs (Google Translate), and your itinerary to cloud storage. This ensures you have backup access even if connectivity is temporarily unavailable.` },
    ],
